Top. 5. ls this distinction is to be used in law, it must be remembered that a res which is, philosophically, corporalis or incorporalis need not be either legally ; it becomes so only is the law takes notice oi it. Thus the sea is a res corporalis in Cicero's sense, but not in that oi the Roman lawyer; it cannot be the object oi rights. Similarly many objects of the intelli· gence have no legal existence whatever.

By res corporalis (sensu legali) is to be understood any limited portion of extemal nature which is not a person, or any tangible object over which ownership can be asserted in a real action : by res incorporalis is to be understood any legal right except the right os ownership itsels. When Gaius (from whom, ii. 12-14, Justinian literally transcribes the whole os this Title) describes obligatio and hereditas as res incorporales he explains that he means the right of the creditor in the former case, and in the latter the right of the person to whom the hereditas is delata to become heres actually by acceptante.
